  • Convenient - Answer and view callers at your door remotely via your mobile iOS or Android device, whether you are at home or abroad. The WiFi IP Doorbell sends a push-notification and directly connects with your smart mobile devices. Advanced Motion Detection can be easily programmed from the App with the ability to define the area of interest, sensitivity, and active time of day/days of week. Easy setup connects to your smart device in minutes.
  • Smart - Our latest upgrade to the original GBF WiFi IP Doorbell adds a Smart Keypad that is programmed through your smart phone; through the App you can remotely change your personal keypad PIN, or generate temporary or permanent PIN codes to grant your guests access to your premises. Set your gate to open automatically during specified time periods and days of week, all done through your App.
  • Secure - Event log of one week can be retrieved through the App, with timeline and video clips that track all events occurring at the outdoor station (Ring-in, App unlock, Keypad unlock, Motion Detection). Multiple clients (smart devices) can be connected to a single IP Doorbell, Multiple doorbells can be accessed together through our free App. Integrated dual-stream ONVIF 1080P IP camera offers a 160 degree wide viewing angle. Illumination LED’s allow for clearer visitor video in low light.
  • Versatile - Two integrated SPDT relays can trigger two different remote door locks or gates, which can be activated directly from your mobile device, and also with an optional push-to-exit button. Internal normally-open dry-contact relay activates with the press of the ‘Bell’ button, allowing for device connection to any existing chime in your premises. WiFi or Wired Ethernet connection. Integrates seamlessly with our GBF WiFi IP indoor monitor.
  • Dependable - Premium Brushed Aluminum faceplate for durability. All-metal Back Box, Weatherproof IP65 rated construction. Always-on blue backlight enables easy user operation in low light conditions. Requires 12VDC 1A Power (adapter included) or can be powered through a wired Ethernet connection using the integrated PoE. 1-year manufacturers warranty. No Subscription Fees for Basic features, Subscription Fees required for optional features (Event Log, Temporary Visitor Codes, and Timed Unlock).

Product description

GBF Smart Video Door Station - your complete solution for a Smart Access Control System for home and office

All-In-One Smart IP Door Station with Smart Keypad-- Calling, Intercom, Unlocking, Monitoring, Access codes, Timed unlock, Missed Call Message...

GBF's Smart Video Doorbell System with Smart Keypad supports video, two-way voice communication, remote release of two different locks, remote programming of custom user PIN codes, a comprehensive event log, programmable 'Timed Unlock' feature, and generation of temporary visitor access codes. You can watch, hear and speak to the person at your door, and unlock the door with your iOS/Android devices (iPhone, iPad, smart phones, and other mobile devices) and with an optional indoor monitor. Works from anywhere your smart device can connect to the internet via WiFi or Data connection. App and basic server service are all free to download and use. Some premium features (extended event log, programmable timed unlock, and temporary PIN code generation) require a subscription.

Premium Contemporary Design with Brushed Aluminum Finish

The hottest heat and the coldest frost will not warp, crack, or fade our Aluminum Alloy faceplate, and the GBF IP Door Station will retain its fresh looks year after year. - All exposed surfaces are made of Aluminum and Galvanized Steel and are theft and vandal resistant.

Main Features

Answer and Monitor your Entry from Anywhere

Receive visitor and motion notifications, and remotely control entry access via your internet-connected smart device.

Live Video with Audio Calls

Answer your visitors and view them at your door with crystal clear video through the built-in 1080P ONVIF compliant camera, all done remotely via your mobile iOS or Android device, whether you are at home or abroad.

Share your doorbell with your family members

Add authorized users of your IP Doorbell through the app. All shared users receive notifications and have access to the IP Doorbell from anywhere their mobile device has an internet connection.

All events are stored and available for review

Activities at your IP Doorbell will be stored on a user-supplied SD card and in the Cloud (optional) . Time-stamped event video clips can be replayed through your app.

More features

Remotely Programmable Smart Keypad

User PIN code and length can be customized through the App.

Control two different Entries with a Swipe

Two Integrated SPDT relays can be used to trigger two different door locks, remotely through your mobile device.

Motion Detection and Alerts

Set your motion detection area, detection sensitivity and schedule directly from your APP.

Integrates with GBF’s WiFi IP Indoor Monitor

Add one or multiple Indoor Monitors to your door station. All indoor monitors and your smart phone will receive ring-in notifications. Multiple monitors can also be configured as an inter-station audio intercom.

Some advanced features

Play a message to your visitor

Create a missed call message to automatically play back to your visitors or guests if you are unable to answer an incoming call, such as while travelling or while in a meeting...

Programmable 'Lock Open' Scheduling

Set your gate to open automatically (optional) during specified time periods and days of week, all done through your App

Create and share temporary Visitor codes

Temporary visitor PIN codes (optional) can be created and shared through the app, with user-programmable expiration times, dates, duration, and code length.

Flexible visitor access codes settings

Program your own access codes for two different doors/gates remotely. Use one smart keypad to control two different locks remotely.

      5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      Great Value
      Reviewed in the United States on August 26, 2022
      I've had a gated driveway for 22 years. I originally installed a "Crown Jewel" Telco based access control. Worked well for several years (using the "land line"), until lightening fried the telco system, then I just used it as a keypad control. No big... See more
      I've had a gated driveway for 22 years. I originally installed a "Crown Jewel" Telco based access control. Worked well for several years (using the "land line"), until lightening fried the telco system, then I just used it as a keypad control. No big deal, esp. since "land line" has been gone for many years from our residence. I've really wanted to upgrade for years, but couldn't find something that would do what I wanted at a reasonable price. Another lightening strike finished off the keypad function of the Crown Jewel and forced me into remediation mode.

      I saw this on Amazon, and was skeptical. Since I was in a pinch, I decided to give it a try, and I'm so glad I did! So, here are the "good/bad/ugly" of the system - and it is mostly "good" (if not great):

      My gate is LONG way from the house through woods. First I have to establish good connection, and our rural location makes cellular access less than ideal (and I don't want a monthly bill). The rural location means internet is also a challenge, so I'll give Starlink a plug here too. Several months we got our Starlink dish, and internet service has been phenomenal. So I purchase several wireless bridges, because I have a long distance and many obstacles to navigate. I am successful at getting internet via. daisy chained bridges to the gate, and I install the GBF keypad. It works amazing. Pictures are good quality, the "call" button works as promised, I'm very happy. Put that with the price (and I priced other systems) and I'm ecstatic.

      Not to say the system is "perfect". I would gladly pay more for a few upgrades. I did paint the outer enclosure black (see image), and I think it improves the appearance. The old Crown Jewel, while susceptible to lightening, was built like a Sherman tank - but this is more like a Volkswagen Beetle. It would take running over with a car to damage the Crown Jewel, but a baseball bat would destroy the GBF unit. They should offer a more robust enclosure as an upgrade.

      As mentioned in another review, the "#CODE#" sequence is odd. What is the purpose of the "#'s" on each side of the code?? This would be an easy win for the programmers if they'd make a modification that made the "#'s" unnecessary.

      Better description than a "bell icon" should indicate the call button. What about "Call"?? I plan to put a label by the keypad that says "#CODE#" for those with codes, so they don't forget about the #'s, and a label by the bell button that says "Call Button". Those labels will distract from the clean look of the unit, but are needed to avoid confusion.

      A 'night vision' option is needed on the camera. All you have is a bright LED that will illuminate the caller, IF they lean in when talking. The type of night vision on products like a Ring security camera would be a welcomed enhancement.

      To finish my review on refocusing on why I give it 5 stars - the unit does everything + more than what the Crown Jewel did - and that unit cost close to $2,000 22 years ago! When setting it up, I had a few questions so I called the technical support number. The person that helped me was FANTASTIC (Thanks Ray!). It is a nice looking unit, and is priced very competitively. I highly recommend this for anyone looking for a gate access control.

      2.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      Has a lot of quirks, some quite bad.
      Reviewed in the United States on February 1, 2023
      It took hours to actually get the thing configured, mostly due to the extremely poor app. The device itself is ok but there are some serious quirks. It is not a grade-A video doorbell for sure. * There seems to be no way to change how the chime sounds (on the... See more
      It took hours to actually get the thing configured, mostly due to the extremely poor app. The device itself is ok but there are some serious quirks. It is not a grade-A video doorbell for sure.

      * There seems to be no way to change how the chime sounds (on the doorbell itself). It dings incessantly if not answered, which really bothers me (and would bother guests as well). I just want it to ding once or twice so the person at the door knows the doorbell was wrung, and that's it. There is no configuration field to do that.

      * You MUST use the POE+ ethernet. The wifi sucks... badly. The video becomes extremely laggy and virtually unusable, even when the base station is close. I've tried multiple combinations and it just doesn't integrate well via Wifi.

      * This thing really wants to talk to the internet, a lot. It would be nice if it had configuration features to turn off all of the cloud junk rather than having to set it up on a dedicated wifi and then unplug the wifi's internet. I don't want mobile device integration. I just want a video doorbell and two displays on the same network in the house and that's it.

      * Audio echos are fairly severe.

      One would think that a product out this long wouldn't have these problems. My mistake was in believing it would be decently good after being available for so long. But no.

      I may have written a review similar to this one before, but after installing the third GBF keypad at my rural property, I want to make sure to let other customers know about my experiences.

      I use these keypads for access control at the entry gates to my property. I have tried three other brands and types of keypads, but ultimately they were all fine products that did not meet my needs for one reason or another.

      I need a keypad that is internet connected and controllable via an iPhone app. The keypad needs to have low latency when speaking to visitors on the videophone feature. It needs to be POE connected so that there is one cable for data and power, and I need to be able to open the gate remotely using the iPhone app. Lastly, a security code or passcode for entry via the numeric keypad is also a necessity for my scenario.

      These keypads offer exactly what I need for a very reasonable price when compared to comparable commercial offerings that are a great deal more expensive.

      Furthermore, GBF Electronics email support has been very good and responsive. Their technical support via telephone is excellent. The person that I have spoken to over the phone (Ray) has been extremely helpful and professional.

      I am very satisfied with the GBF products.

    • Neighborhood Mechanic
      4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      Exactly what was needed
      Reviewed in the United States on October 28, 2022
      I purchased this to work with my ghost controls auto gate opener. This has normally open option as well as normally closed option for your unlocking needs. I needed normally open. The only downside to this entire system was getting it connected to the internet... See more
      I purchased this to work with my ghost controls auto gate opener. This has normally open option as well as normally closed option for your unlocking needs. I needed normally open.

      The only downside to this entire system was getting it connected to the internet using an iPhone with iOS.

      Tip: I didn’t get it working with their instructions. After talking with Ray at support, I just added a device in the app and did the sound wave option for adding a device. However it didn’t smoothly work. For me this is the steps to get it connected:

      Download app, plug power into keypad and wait about a minute before doing anything. After a minute press and hold the button on the back panel next to the Ethernet port until you hear the first set of beep tones. Let go of the button. Wait about 20 seconds for the keypad to make another noise. At this time I opened the app, added a device, I did NOT going into the setting in the app, just add device. Make sure your in a somewhat quiet area, as your phone will make sounds they keypad will hear and start programming itself through the sounds. After starting the process my keypad lights lit up and it made a noise, my app said they keypad was attempting to connect but would fail everytime. When you get to this point back out of that area in the app, do not do anything to the keypad, and then add a device using the QR code on the device. Instantly everything worked. Done.

      I have a reolink security nvr system at my home and wanted to add its camera feed to it. This was a process. Download the app called ControlCam2 2 and find your camera on the network, this will give you the ip address to the camera. From what I can tell, this is the easiest way to get that up address. After you have the ip address, go into your onvif setup and use port 8000, username and password should both be admin.

      My system is very laggy and won’t actively stream the camera, but that’s how I got it to work. My issue is with my system not this keypad.

      Overall, it was a little confusing to get setup, the manual could use a complete overhaul for guidance. But to make up for it, they have a die t number to call, they are very helpful and will sit on the phone trying to help you get through any issues you are having.

      If anyone is wondering, I set the wire harness up in lock 1, hooked the blue wire from the keypad to the com port on my ghost controls panel, and the green wire from the keypad to the CYC port on the ghost controls panel. This is all you need to use this keypad with that setup. These are the 2 wires that will cycle a normally open circuit lock. The resister supplied is not needed but is a good precautionary step for feedback signals.

      If you are concerned about anything, the support at GBF is amazing, specifically Ray walked me through all my questions and helped at every step I needed.

      3.0 out of 5 stars
      It mostly works
      Reviewed in the United States on June 24, 2024
      I bought this to use as a controller for the gate out at the driveway. I was replacing a battery powered unit by mighty mule that didnt have a camera. I did not want to replace the existing pole so it made it quite a challenge modifying things to mount together. The biggest... See more
      I bought this to use as a controller for the gate out at the driveway. I was replacing a battery powered unit by mighty mule that didnt have a camera. I did not want to replace the existing pole so it made it quite a challenge modifying things to mount together. The biggest issue mounting was that where the wires plug into the circuit board requires space beyond the mounting surface, so this cannot be mounted flush unless you can cut a big hole behind it, especially if you are running wired ethernet. It would also be nice it these were compatible with various voltages. My gate controller has 24v output for devices like this, but this will only accept 12v. The instructions did not include wiring instructions for this application but I was able to get it working after a couple of attempts. The wireless on this kinda sucks. I tried using the included omni directional antenna and it did not work a couple hundred feet away from the access point even though cell phones have several bars of wifi signal at the gate. I replaced the included antenna with a +13db directional antenna and it works better, but it still loses signal once in a while and I am not able to use the gate opener from the app, and the video connection can be choppy and intermittent. I contacted support and their suggestion was to buy an additional $100 wifi bridge to connect to the device. Hands down the worst part of this is the app they are using. What a horrible piece of crap. I actively avoid using. I have had to turn off alerts, even though this is one of the features I bought it for. The app sends notifications when there is movement, but the app turns the phone screen on and will not allow the screen to turn off no matter what the phone settings are. If my screen is set to turn off after 10 seconds of inactivity the app takes over and ignores my preferences. The problem here is that I might have my phone in a pocket or a backpack and I done hear it or check it for an hour or 2, now my phone is overheating and my battery is dead. I setup a specific area of detection but that gets ignored, especially at night which turns on my screen and never lets it turn off. The features listed on the ad are not included feature, such as the one week of event logs (one place it lists this as a feature, another place it does say this is a paid subscription). The device came with a free trial subscription but I found that events still disappeared way before the 7 day limit. One place in ad it lists the ability to give visitors their own codes, then later they tell you its also part of the subscription. When we did have the motion alerts setup sometimes only one phone or the other got the notification even though we were in the same room, sometimes we both got the notifications, sometimes neither of us were notified. Overall the device is good if the application will work for your install and you are willing to spend some $$$ to adapt it to your needs, the biggest downfall by far is the app.
